  "prompt": "Can we use nuclear explosions to power a spacecraft?",
  "response": "The concept of using nuclear explosions to propel a spacecraft, known as nuclear pulse propulsion, has been studied seriously, most notably in the Project Orion program in the 1950s and 1960s. The basic idea involves repeatedly detonating nuclear explosives behind a spacecraft to create a series of propulsive pulses.\n\nKey points about nuclear pulse propulsion:\n\n1. Theoretical advantages:\n- Extremely high potential thrust\n- Very high specific impulse\n- Potential for interplanetary and even interstellar travel\n\n2. Technical challenges:\n- Massive radiation risks\n- Extreme engineering complexity\n- Environmental and political concerns about launching nuclear devices\n- Potential for widespread contamination\n\n3. Current status:\n- The concept remains theoretical\n- No nuclear pulse propulsion spacecraft has ever been built\n- Modern space programs focus on other propulsion technologies like ion drives and chemical rockets\n\nWhile scientifically intriguing, nuclear pulse propulsion remains impractical with current technology and international treaties. Most space agencies consider it too risky and problematic for practical implementation.\n\nTheoretical designs like Project Orion demonstrated the concept's potential, but practical and political obstacles have prevented its development.",
